    Solution

    • Get your data into column A of a spreadsheet, from A1 to A1000.
    • Sort your data using Data, Sort sheet, Sort sheet by column A.
    • Calculate the indices of the percentiles:
      • For the 2.5th percentile: \(0.025\cdot 1000=25\)
      • For the 16th percentile: \(0.16\cdot 1000=160\)
      • For the 50th percentile: \(0.6\cdot 1000=500\)
      • For the 84th percentile: \(0.84\cdot 1000=840\)
      • For the 97.5th percentile: \(0.975\cdot 1000=975\)
    • Find the values at those rows.
      • The value in cell A\(25\) should be \(76\).
      • The value in cell A\(160\) should be \(86\).
      • The value in cell A\(500\) should be \(97\).
      • The value in cell A\(840\) should be \(107\).
      • The value in cell A\(975\) should be \(118\).

    You can see answers as the color changes in the sorted list below.


    Iâ€™ve produced a dot plot that helps visualize these percentiles.


    You might notice the five answers are spaced evenly-ish.

    \[86-76=10\] \[97-86=11\] \[107-97=10\] \[118-107=11\]

    This is not a coincidence. Because each repetition of the simulation involves adding a bunch of independent random variables, we expect the output values to be normally distributed.

    If youâ€™ve studied a lot of probability, you might know about standard deviation. If you look up discrete uniform distribution, you can find the formula for the standard deviation for a 6-sided die or a 8-sided die.

    \[\mathrm{SD(1d6)} = \sqrt{\frac{6^2-1}{12}} \approx 1.708\] \[\mathrm{SD(1d8)} = \sqrt{\frac{8^2-1}{12}} \approx 2.291\]

    If youâ€™ve REALLY studied probability, you might know one of the most important reasons we use standard deviation: if random variables X and Y are independent, then \(\mathrm{SD(X+Y)=\sqrt{SD(X)^2+SD(Y)^2}}\). This implies the following:

    \[\mathrm{SD(7d6+16d8)} = \sqrt{7\cdot1.708^2+16\cdot2.291^2} \approx 10.2\]

    To learn more, read about the central limit theorem and the 68-95-99.7 rule.

    If youâ€™ve studied a lot of probability, you might know about standard deviation. If you look up discrete uniform distribution, you can find the formula for the standard deviation for a 10-sided die or a 12-sided die.

    If youâ€™ve REALLY studied probability, you might know one of the most important reasons we use standard deviation: if random variables X and Y are independent, then \(\mathrm{SD(X+Y)=\sqrt{SD(X)^2+SD(Y)^2}}\). This implies the following:

    \[\mathrm{SD(9d10+16d12)} = \sqrt{9\cdot2.872^2+16\cdot3.452^2} \approx 16.3\]

    To learn more, read about the central limit theorem and the 68-95-99.7 rule.
